<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,152,755]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,319,226,252]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Remarks.</emphasis>
The identity of this species is taken from 
<bibRefCitation author="Wagner, W." box="[830,1061,226,252]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="77 - 212" refId="ref18937" refString="Wagner, W. (1939). Die Zikaden des Mainzer Beckens. Zugleich eine Revision der Kirschbaumschen Arten aus der Umgebung von Wiesbaden. Jahrbucher des Vereins fur Naturkunde im Herzogthum Nassau, 86, 77 - 212." type="journal article" year="1939">Wagner (1939: 163</bibRefCitation>
, figs 240–241). 
<bibRefCitation author="Wagner, W." box="[1258,1435,226,252]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="77 - 212" refId="ref18937" refString="Wagner, W. (1939). Die Zikaden des Mainzer Beckens. Zugleich eine Revision der Kirschbaumschen Arten aus der Umgebung von Wiesbaden. Jahrbucher des Vereins fur Naturkunde im Herzogthum Nassau, 86, 77 - 212." type="journal article" year="1939">Wagner (1939)</bibRefCitation>
renamed 
<taxonomicName authority="Marsh" authorityName="Marsh, Fieber" authorityYear="1872" box="[259,613,265,291]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Thamnotettix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coronifer">
<emphasis box="[259,529,265,290]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Thamnotettix coronifer</emphasis>
Marsh
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Fieber (1872)" authorityName="Fieber" authorityYear="1872" box="[625,860,265,291]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Maiestas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sensu">
<emphasis box="[625,690,265,290]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Fieber, F. X." box="[697,860,265,291]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref15418" refString="Fieber, F. X. (1872). Katalog der europaischen Cicadinen, nach Originalien mit Benutzung der neuesten Literatur. Carl Gerold's Sohn, Wien. 19 pp." type="book" year="1872">Fieber (1872)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagner, Ribaut" authorityYear="1952" box="[903,1045,265,290]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Deltocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schmidtgeni">
<emphasis box="[903,1045,265,290]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">schmidtgeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and figured what he presumed to be the same species from 
<collectingCountry box="[473,586,304,330]" name="Germany" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Germany</collectingCountry>
(see 
<figureCitation box="[654,761,304,330]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–20" captionStartId="48.[151,270,1712,1736]" captionTargetBox="[177,1407,199,1647]" captionTargetId="figure-58@48.[151,1436,141,1747]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURES 17–20. Maiestas species. 17, M. schmidtgeni (Wagner), o: aedeagus lateral view (Dagestan except o: after Wagner, 1939, Fig. 240). 18, M. beieri (Dlabola) (holotype, and o: paratype). 19, Maiestas sp. (Israel, Hadera). 20, Maiestas sp. (Israel, Upper Galilee)." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 17o</figureCitation>
). These figures match those specimens examined here (BMNH) from S. Europe and the Mediterranean (
<collectingCountry box="[749,835,342,368]" name="France" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">France</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[848,939,342,368]" name="Austria" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Austria</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[951,1034,342,368]" name="Russia" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Russia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1047,1134,342,368]" name="Greece" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Greece</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1147,1251,342,368]" name="Hungary" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Hungary</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1312,1402,342,368]" name="Turkey" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Turkey</collectingCountry>
), a feature of which is the elongate aedeagal shaft, slightly angled at midlength (
<figureCitation box="[1044,1146,381,407]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–20" captionStartId="48.[151,270,1712,1736]" captionTargetBox="[177,1407,199,1647]" captionTargetId="figure-58@48.[151,1436,141,1747]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURES 17–20. Maiestas species. 17, M. schmidtgeni (Wagner), o: aedeagus lateral view (Dagestan except o: after Wagner, 1939, Fig. 240). 18, M. beieri (Dlabola) (holotype, and o: paratype). 19, Maiestas sp. (Israel, Hadera). 20, Maiestas sp. (Israel, Upper Galilee)." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 17k</figureCitation>
). Other specimens found under this name in BMNH and NMW, from the Middle East, and N. and W. Africa, were found to have a shorter, broader and more evenly curved aedeagal shaft (see 
<figureCitation box="[856,1018,458,484]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–20" captionStartId="48.[151,270,1712,1736]" captionTargetBox="[177,1407,199,1647]" captionTargetId="figure-58@48.[151,1436,141,1747]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURES 17–20. Maiestas species. 17, M. schmidtgeni (Wagner), o: aedeagus lateral view (Dagestan except o: after Wagner, 1939, Fig. 240). 18, M. beieri (Dlabola) (holotype, and o: paratype). 19, Maiestas sp. (Israel, Hadera). 20, Maiestas sp. (Israel, Upper Galilee)." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Figs 19k, 20k</figureCitation>
, and 
<figureCitation box="[1078,1124,458,484]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–24" captionStartId="49.[151,270,1783,1807]" captionTargetBox="[200,1367,230,1716]" captionTargetId="figure-67@49.[151,1436,201,1822]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURES 21–24. Maiestas species. 21, Maiestas sp. o: aedeagus, lateral view; p, apex of aedeagus, dorsolateral view (Egypt, Assiut, NMW). 22, Maiestas sp. (Nigeria). 23, Maiestas sp., o, p: apex of aedeagus, dorsolateral and dorsal view (Sudan). 24, Maiestas mica (Kramer), o: apex of aedeagus, dorsolateral view (Liberia, paratype)." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">21k</figureCitation>
) and some a straighter and longer style apical process (see 
<figureCitation box="[522,619,497,523]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–24" captionStartId="49.[151,270,1783,1807]" captionTargetBox="[200,1367,230,1716]" captionTargetId="figure-67@49.[151,1436,201,1822]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURES 21–24. Maiestas species. 21, Maiestas sp. o: aedeagus, lateral view; p, apex of aedeagus, dorsolateral view (Egypt, Assiut, NMW). 22, Maiestas sp. (Nigeria). 23, Maiestas sp., o, p: apex of aedeagus, dorsolateral and dorsal view (Sudan). 24, Maiestas mica (Kramer), o: apex of aedeagus, dorsolateral view (Liberia, paratype)." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 21f</figureCitation>
). See also remarks under 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dlabola" baseAuthorityYear="1964" box="[920,988,497,522]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Maiestas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beieri">
<emphasis box="[920,988,497,522]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">beieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,152,755]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
With reference to French records of this species it has been reported from Toulouse by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ribaut, H." box="[1215,1381,536,562]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 474" refId="ref18340" refString="Ribaut, H. (1952). Homopteres Auchenorhynques. II (Jassidae). Faune de France, 57, 1 - 474." type="journal article" year="1952">Ribaut (1952)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[151,242,574,600]" name="France" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Corsica</collectingCountry>
and Dordogne by della 
<bibRefCitation author="Giustina, W. della" box="[536,788,574,600]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="350" refId="ref15734" refString="Giustina, W. della (1989). Homopteres Cicadellidae Vol. 3. Faune de France, 73, 350." type="journal article" year="1989">Giustina (1989: 127)</bibRefCitation>
who considered it to be rather rare. However, Benoit Nusillard writes (pers. comm.) that it is found in numbers on the garrigue north of Montpellier (Hérault), around Valence and Montélimar (Drôme) (mixed with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Marshall" baseAuthorityYear="1866" box="[802,1002,652,677]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Recilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coronifer">
<emphasis box="[802,1002,652,677]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Recilia coronifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and in the Camargue around Arles (Bouches du Rhône) and there strongly attracted to UV light. Specimens were collected between 26 of June and 11 October, with possibly two generations.
</paragraph>
